      <text>
        The descent is easier than the climb—gravity helps, for one thing. My legs still ache from yesterday's ascent, but going downhill requires different muscles—more control than power. Scout bounces ahead, clearly enjoying the momentum— they've perfected the art of controlled rolling on slopes.

        Oakshade is quiet this morning, more contemplative than usual—even for a tree.

        I say, "You're thinking about the question."

        Oakshade admits, "Yes—It was well-presented. Elder Heartwood will have much to consider."

        I ask, "How long do these things usually take?"

        Mossmantle makes a thoughtful sound and replies, "Depends on the complexity—simple questions, weeks; deeper matters, months—sometimes seasons."

        Months—possibly seasons. I try not to think too hard about what "seasons" means when you're a being that measures time in tree rings.

        Oakshade adds, "But the answers are always worth waiting for—Elder Heartwood sees connections we cannot. Patterns across vast timescales."

        There's absolute confidence in their voice—not hope—certainty.

        I say, "Tell me about a time Elder Heartwood answered a question—what kind of wisdom are we talking about?"

        Oakshade's branches rustle—pleasure at being asked—and Oakshade says, "Seventeen seasons ago, Territory Seven faced a mineral depletion—their soil was exhausted, renewal processes failing. They presented the question: how do we restore balance?"

        Mossmantle continues, "Elder Heartwood considered for three months—then provided guidance not just about minerals but about the entire cycle: water flow patterns, root distribution, microbial partnerships—a complete framework."

        I ask, "It worked?"

        Oakshade answers, "Territory Seven is thriving now—the answer addressed not just the immediate problem but the underlying systems. That's Elder Heartwood's gift—seeing the whole ecosystem."

        We navigate a particularly steep section. I use my hands to steady myself on rocks while Scout bounces down in controlled hops. The valley floor is coming into view below.

        Mossmantle offers another example and says, "Twelve seasons ago, two territories had a boundary dispute—resources overlapping, maintenance responsibilities unclear—they couldn't agree on division."

        I ask, "What did Elder Heartwood say?"

        Oakshade replies, "Don't divide—collaborate. Create joint maintenance agreements. Share resources based on need, not location." Oakshade adds, "The answer transformed how they thought about boundaries entirely."

        I can hear the admiration in both their voices—these aren't just stories, they're foundational examples of why Elder Heartwood matters.

        I say, "So Elder Heartwood doesn't just answer questions."

        ¶

        I continue, "Elder Heartwood reframes them."

        Mossmantle sounds delighted and says, "*Exactly!* You understand— the question about human survival needs—Elder Heartwood won't just list requirements—the response will explain how to think about cross-framework care."
      </text>
