        That actually does sound helpful — not just 'humans need X Y Z' but 'here's how to approach incompatible needs systematically.' Maybe this really will work.

        I reach down to pat Scout's sphere and ask, "What do you think, Scout? Will Elder Heartwood help us figure this out?"

        An enthusiastic bounce — Scout is optimistic about everything.

        The plateau levels out into familiar rolling hills. We're back in the lower elevations now, retracing our path from two days ago. The crystalline rocks Scout loved are still there, catching the light.

        Buddy says quietly in my mind, "Kira — I've been analyzing the Elder Heartwood consultation framework. It's quite sophisticated — distributed knowledge processing, temporal integration of data patterns — well… yes? It's fascinating — the information processing capacity must be extraordinary — all those root networks, the symbiotic partnerships — sorry, I got excited — but it *is* exciting."

        I smile despite myself. Buddy's enthusiasm is endearing, even when it's about analyzing alien plant cognition.

        We walk through the afternoon, covering ground we climbed two days ago. Everything looks different going the opposite direction — I notice details I missed on the way up: a particular rock formation, the way water trickles down a cliff face, Scout's favorite bouncing spot.

        I ask, "How much have I changed?" Not really meaning to say it out loud.

        Oakshade turns slightly and asks, "Changed?"

        I say, "Since you met me — at the Territory Two boundary, what, three days ago? Am I different?"

        Oakshade replies, "More confident — you trust the rhythm now. Your body knows the pattern of long walking."

        Mossmantle adds, "Less hesitant — you read terrain better and make decisions faster."

        Huh — three days, and it's visible.

        I say, "The whole journey — nine days through three territories, six different guides. I've learned a lot, haven't I?"

        Oakshade agrees, "About trust, adaptation, communication across differences."

        Mossmantle observes, "Scout has learned too — partnership requires both sides growing."

        Scout bounces — agreement and pride. We're a team now.

        ¶

        But underneath the real growth, the genuine learning… we're still waiting for *THE answer*. The one that will actually explain how to keep me alive properly.

        I've learned to walk long distances, to trust plant guides, and that different territories have different personalities I can adapt to. Those are real skills.

        But they don't solve the fundamental problem — the plants don't understand human needs, and I can't explain them in ways that make sense to plant frameworks. We need someone who can bridge that gap, someone with enough wisdom to translate between incompatible systems.

        Elder Heartwood.

        I ask carefully, "Do you think the answer will come before I… before it's urgent?"
      </text>
