        Oakshade and Mossmantle are quiet for a moment.

        Oakshade finally says, "Elder Heartwood understands timing — when something is critical, responses come faster."

        Mossmantle adds firmly, "Your survival is critical — Elder Heartwood will know that."

        I want to believe them — standing in that vast grove, feeling the ground shift as Elder Heartwood acknowledged our question. That felt real and important, like we'd reached someone who actually understood.

        The journey taught me competence, but Elder Heartwood will teach the plants how to actually help me — both matter, but only one solves the survival problem.

        We reach the evening campsite, the same sheltered spot between rock formations where we stayed two nights ago. The moss patches are still soft, the spring still trickling — territory maintenance keeps these places ready.

        Scout and I claim our moss patch; my legs are tired but satisfied-tired, not injured-tired — good walking today.

        Oakshade says, "Tomorrow we reach Territory Two's boundary — Streamwalker and Brightbloom will guide you back through the wetlands."

        I continue, "And then Leafwhisper and Rootwalker through the forest — back to the facility in... what, six more days?"

        Mossmantle confirms, "About that — full journey complete. Fifteen days total."

        Fifteen days — half a month on Earth — that's not nothing.

        I eat my evening rations — mushroom paste I no longer taste, nutrient bars Buddy assures me are adequate. Scout curls up beside me. The sunset is spectacular from this elevation: purple sky deepening to violet, stars beginning to show.

        I say to Oakshade and Mossmantle, "Thank you — for guiding me here, for presenting the question so well."

        Oakshade replies, "It was an honor — your question matters, and the answer will benefit many."

        Mossmantle adds, "Not just you — understanding cross-framework care, that's wisdom every territory needs."

        Oh — I hadn't thought about that. If Elder Heartwood figures out how to help plants care for humans, that knowledge spreads everywhere — it's not just solving my problem, it's creating new understanding for the whole network.

        That feels bigger than I expected.

        I joke weakly, "So no pressure."

        Oakshade says serenely, "The pressure is on Elder Heartwood — you simply asked the question; now you wait with hope."

        Wait with hope.

        I can do that — I've learned patience over these nine days, to trust processes that don't make immediate sense, and that plant wisdom works on different timescales but it does work.

        Elder Heartwood will think about human survival needs — will consider frameworks and bridges and incompatible systems — will draw on countless seasons of experience.

        And when the answer comes — weeks or months from now — it will be worth waiting for — it has to be.

        ¶

        Because the journey taught me a lot, but it didn't teach the plants how to actually keep me alive.
      </text>
